<DOC><DOCNO> AP900513-0001 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-90 2326EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Cuba     05-13 0236</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Cuba,0244</SECOND><HEAD>Cuba Pins Economic Development Hopes On Private Foreign TourismInvestors</HEAD><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cuban President Fidel Castro is encouragingforeign investors to develop resort hotels in hopes of offsettingan economic crisis with tourist spending, the Mexican governmentnews agency reported Sunday.   Castro kicked off a new beach resort construction program at theinauguration of a hotel built by private Spanish investors withsupport from the Cuban government tourism developer Cubanacan, theNotimex agency reported.   At the inauguration Thursday, Castro said Cuba plans to spend$10,000 to develop hundreds of beach sites, Notimex reported.   The government is offering 10 years' tax exemption to privatetourism business developers, Notimex quoted Cubanacan directorAbraham Maciques as saying.   The newly inaugurated Sol Palmeras Hotel is the first of eighthotels to be built with private foreign investment and governmentmoney in the cities of Varadero, Santiago de Cuba and Havana, thenews agency said.   Spanish, Finnish and Soviet investors are working with Cubanacanto build the hotels, Notimex reported.   It said 2,000 new hotel rooms, are expected to be ready by theend of 1990, and most of them will be in four-star hotels.   The Sol Palmeras is part of a development in Varadero, 60 milesfrom Havana, Notimex reported. The hotel has 400 rooms and 32luxury suites.   The Varadero tourist center is expected to generate $900 milliona year, the news agency reported.</TEXT></DOC>